Text: Goals for the week.
Increase the interactivity of the webpages, particularly embedding audio and video of exhibits.
Populating pages with relevant content, including acquiring real audio from the client, as proof of concept.
What went well?.
This week I felt a lot came out of our team meetings.
Important discussions took place around the direction we wish to take and how we envisage the finished product.

For example, when we recalled the potential number of exhibits on displayÂ around the museum and whether the platform we have built will have the capacity to hold data for such a large number, we began throwing around the idea of building a database.
ThisÂ soon proved more work and time than we are able to give.

ThenÂ there arose a question of how to display each section (corresponding to an exhibit) - whether on its own web page or as a mere section on a webpageÂ that a QR code will lead them to through a section ID.
We decided on the latter, as a more efficient programming process and also considering the complexity of handing over that many webpages to the client.
I found these discussions interesting,Â firstlyÂ because it was the first time we had considered the physical handover of our work.

What's more, discussing the alternative ways of displaying content to the user, forced us toÂ really consider user experience more in depth and made us realise how much closer we were to having our product used by a real user.
What did not go well?.
There had been initial shock at how much revision was needed before jumping straight into web programming at the end of last week and throughout this week.
I had assumed that it would be easy enough to jump back into and resume where I left off with it over a year earlier.
However as I first began working on our code, it was at a much slower/less efficient rate than I had first anticipated for myself.

It was only when examining the code in detail with the team and discussing its contents, that things began to fully return to memory and I could begin to reach a greater level of confidence with it all.
What would I do differently?.
Faced with the same goals, I would start working on the code as soon as an initial design or plan is set out.
The earlier knowledge gaps are identified, the quicker these can be addressed and prevented from becoming a setback or risk affecting the overall timeliness of the project delivery.
I can gain skills quicker and acquire a deeper knowledge of whatever is at hand when I give myself the most possible time to work on this.
This is an important piece of learning for me as the project draws to a close.

I realise that in order to get the most out of the projects to come, it is necessary to reflect and build on existing skills before embarking on a team project so as to be the best possible asset to the team and client, but also so that I can give myself more time and capacity right from the start to acquire new skills.
What am I satisfied with?.
It has been satisfying to observe the progress that has been made since we first started this project.
Over the first 2 weeks, it had felt like there was not enough time to handover something tangible to our clients.
At this point in the project, we only had HTML skeletons from a bootstrap template and vague visual designs.
I was hard to envisage that with such limited experience, I would be able to contribute to building something complex for a real-world entity, such as the Otago Museum.
Now it is a fully interactive set of webpages, ready for user testing on our clientâ€™s premises: .

Although our webpages are intended as a proof of concept at this stage, we are confident that what we are about to deliver at the end of this week will be an invaluable resource for engaging museum visitors through the use of interactive technology.
